# Excel Is Not the Problem. Poor Data Architecture Is.

One misconception I often see in digital transformation projects is that Excel is treated as the problem.

It isn't.

Excel is simply a tool.

The real questions should be:

* Where does the data come from?
* Is there a single source of truth?
* Can the data be refreshed automatically?
* Is everyone looking at the same version of the data?

If those questions are answered properly, Excel can become an excellent reporting and analysis tool for many small and medium-sized businesses.

In my opinion, business users should not spend their time thinking about databases.

Business users need answers, not technology.

If an automatically refreshed Excel workbook can provide reliable, consistent, and timely information, then it has already achieved its business objective.

The focus should therefore be on the quality and governance of the data source, rather than replacing Excel simply because it is perceived as "old technology."

A stable Single Source of Truth is far more valuable than adopting the latest data platform without solving the underlying data problems.

Technology should remain behind the scenes.

Business users should only notice that the data is accurate, available, and trustworthy.
